I prefer the wonderful, strange, eccentric side of LA – a twisted, surreal collective of David Lynch, Chuck Bukowski and Hunter S Thompson. I dropped my bags off at the trusty Redbury hotel where each room is like a small apartment with its own kitchen. I almost always stay there when I visit the city as it reminds me of home. There are a few things I always try to do in LA, good-for-the-soul things. One is to go to the Dresden, an old club/restaurant where Marty and Elaine have been performing for nearly 40 years. They play the standards, wear matching outfits and argue with one another while performing. They are not as young as they used to be but they are the history and essence of that place, and will leave a colourful legacy.
